SQL Injection Single Column Data Aggregation Techniques
When an application filter contains multiple columns, extracting assets is straightforward. However, when your vulnerability scanning isolates only a single text-friendly column, pulling data sequentially breaks the relational mapping. If you run multiple disjointed attempts, you lose the link that connects a specific user to their corresponding password hash.
The Solution String Concatenation
To bypass design layout constraints and extract multiple database variables simultaneously through a single text slot, we merge string fields using a unique custom separator character such as ~ or -.
Inside Database: [administrator] (User) + [s3cure123] (Password)
Merged Injected Output: administrator~s3cure123
Cross Platform Syntax Blueprint
Different relational database backends implement completely distinct operators to handle string concatenation:
Oracle and PostgreSQL Double Pipe Matrix
Uses the binary double-pipe || operator.
' UNION SELECT username || '~' || password FROM users--
MySQL Concatenation Function
Uses the native built-in CONCAT() function loop.
' UNION SELECT CONCAT(username, '~', password) FROM users--
Note: Always ensure a space or trailing comment sequence follows the payload according to target filtering configurations.
Microsoft SQL Server MS SQL
Uses the standard arithmetic addition operator +.
' UNION SELECT username + '~' + password FROM users--
Core Hacking Takeaway
CRITICAL RULE: Never forget to write the explicit text delimiter like '~' when crafting your extraction payloads. Without a clear delimiter, the data blocks will bleed together, making it impossible to separate a username from its password string cleanly during high-volume data collection.
